{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, the poem \"Aaftab\" (*The Sun*) directly apostrophizes the sun as the vital soul of the cosmos: the force binding time and space, causing existence to emerge from non-being, and embodying heart, mind, soul, and conscious light itself—bestowing awareness and reason upon humanity.[^1]\n\n\"Mehr-e-roshan\" (*The Bright Sun*, lit. from the opening image of the \"shining sun\" vanishing at dusk) uses the sun's setting as a metaphor for worldly transience and death, which unveils night's mysteries and spurs the poet's inquiry to the grave's \"sleepers in dust\" about the afterlife: a realm hoped to be \"ablaze with Love’s transcendent light\" rather than darkness.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 14 (*Aaftab*), translation, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/14-aaftab/translation/#p-96b3da).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 32 (*Mehr-e-roshan*), translation, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/32-mehr-e-roshan/translation/#p-202a06).",
